The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, January 31, 2004 				 Chambers happy
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Jan. 30: India Inc is pleased with the governments gravy train of poll-eve lollies.																								Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) president Anand Mahindra welcomed the decision of the ministry of railways on maintaining the status quo on freight and passenger tariff this year too.																								Federation of Indian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Ficci) president Yogendra Kumar Modi said, Innovative customer focused services such as e-ticketing, train reservations through mobile phones and the introduction of 17 Sampark Kranti express trains are laudable measures.																								The Rs 20,000-crore programme for execution and completion of railway projects in remote and backward areas is a step in the right direction, industry associations said. They also felt that placing higher emphasis on railway safety by providing an enhanced outlay of Rs 2,795 crore under the special railway safety fund is a positive step.																								Indian business also felt that the completion of all pending projects within a period of five years would encourage and add to development work. 																								Besides, an increase in plan allocation by Rs 1,000 crore in the revised estimate from Rs 12,918 crore to Rs 13,918 crore would prove beneficial. 
